# **7. Seller Draft Review — Webflow CMS**

## **7.1 Architecture Decision**

The seller draft review UI has two implementation options. Choose based on Webflow plan and comfort with embeds.

|  | **Option A: Webflow CMS Native** | **Option B: Webflow + Custom Embed** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Approach | Sales page fields mapped to Webflow CMS. Seller edits via Webflow Editor. | Webflow page embeds a lightweight JS editor that reads/writes Supabase directly. |
| Pros | No custom code. Full Webflow support. Visual editor for seller. | Real-time. No Webflow CMS item limits. More control over UX. |
| Cons | Webflow Editor access required for each seller (not scalable). CMS item limits. | Requires Claude Code to write embed JS. Slightly more complex. |
| Recommendation | Use for first 20 founding sellers — manually managed. | Build from seller 21 onwards when volume demands it. |

## **7.2 Webflow CMS Fields — Sales Page Template**

Create a Webflow CMS Collection called 'Products' with the following fields. Claude Code can generate the Webflow Designer configuration steps.

- Plain Text: Product Title, Headline, Subheadline, CTA Primary Text, CTA Secondary Text

- Rich Text: Problem Statement, Feature Descriptions, Use Cases

- Multi-Image: Screenshots (up to 8)

- Video Link: Demo Video URL

- Number: Price (Licensed), Price (Exclusive)

- Option: Status (Draft / Live / Archived)

- Reference: Seller (links to Sellers collection)

**CLAUDE CODE PROMPT — WEBFLOW CMS SETUP**

| I am building a marketplace called FORGE on Webflow. I need to create two CMS Collections: Collection 1: Sellers Fields: Name (Plain Text), Bio (Rich Text), Avatar (Image), Tool Tags (Multi-reference or Option), Verified (Switch) Collection 2: Products Fields: Title, Headline, Subheadline, Problem Statement (Rich Text), Screenshots (Multi-Image, max 8), Demo Video URL (Plain Text), Price Licensed (Number), Price Exclusive (Number), Status (Option: Draft/Live/Archived), Seller (Reference to Sellers) Give me step-by-step instructions to create these in Webflow Designer. Then show me how to connect a product detail page template to this CMS. |
| --- |

# **8. Email Notifications — Resend Integration**

Two transactional emails are required for the MVP seller onboarding flow. Both are triggered by Make and sent via Resend.

### **Email 1 — Draft Ready Notification**

Sent when the AI sales page generation is complete. Seller clicks through to review their draft.

- Trigger: Make step after successful Supabase write

- To: seller email (from Supabase auth)

- Subject: 'Your FORGE listing draft is ready to review'

- Body: product name, link to draft in Webflow Editor, estimated review time (5 minutes)

### **Email 2 — Listing Live Notification**

Sent when seller publishes their listing. Includes the public URL and share prompt.

- Trigger: Supabase webhook when products.status changes to 'live'

- To: seller email

- Subject: 'Your FORGE listing is live — [Product Name]'

- Body: public listing URL, share on LinkedIn/X prompt, dashboard link

**CLAUDE CODE PROMPT — RESEND IN MAKE**

| Configure a Resend email module in Make (using HTTP module with Resend API). Resend API endpoint: POST https://api.resend.com/emails Auth: Bearer {{RESEND_API_KEY}} Email 1 — Draft Ready:   from: noreply@getforge.io   to: {{seller_email}}   subject: 'Your FORGE listing draft is ready — {{product_title}}'   html: [clean HTML email with product name, review link, FORGE branding] Generate the HTML email template and the Make HTTP module config. Keep the email minimal and professional — dark header, amber CTA button. |
| --- |

# **9. Claude Code Session Plan**

The build is organised into 8 Claude Code sessions. Each session has a single clear objective and produces a testable output before the next session begins. Do not combine sessions — this prevents context bleed and failed implementations.

| **#** | **Session** | **Objective** | **Done When** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Supabase Foundation | Create project, run schema migration, configure RLS, test auth signup | Can register user via Supabase dashboard + SQL runs without errors |
| 2 | Webflow Structure | Create CMS collections, build page templates, connect domain | Products + Sellers CMS collections exist with correct fields |
| 3 | Registration Flow | Build Webflow registration + profile form, connect to Supabase Auth via Make | Test user can register and row appears in Supabase sellers table |
| 4 | Product Submission Form | Build Webflow product form, trigger Make on submit, log payload | Form submits, Make receives payload, logged in Make history |
| 5 | Firecrawl Module | Add Firecrawl step to Make, test with 3 real product URLs | 3 test URLs return structured markdown + screenshot URL |
| 6 | Claude API Module | Add Claude API step to Make, test sales page generation end-to-end | 3 test products generate valid JSON sales page output |
| 7 | Supabase Write + Email | Write generated content to Supabase, trigger draft-ready email | Supabase rows created, Resend email arrives in inbox |
| 8 | Publish Flow + Live Page | Seller edits draft in Webflow, publishes, live page renders correctly | Public product URL loads correct content from CMS |

# **10. Risks ****&**** Mitigations**

| **Risk** | **Impact** | **Mitigation** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Firecrawl returns empty/thin content for SPAs | Claude has nothing to generate from — poor output quality | Add manual description field to product form as fallback. Validate markdown length before Claude step. |
| Claude API generates generic copy | Seller rejects draft, trust in platform drops | Invest in prompt iteration. Add seller context fields (target customer, key differentiator) to submission form to enrich Claude input. |
| Webflow CMS item limits hit at scale | Cannot add new product listings | Webflow CMS limit is 10,000 items on Business plan. Migrate to Supabase-driven custom front-end at 500+ products. |
| Make scenario fails silently | Seller submits URL, nothing happens, no feedback | Add error handling branch in Make. If any step fails: log to Supabase error_log table + send internal alert email. |
| Seller publishes low-quality listing | Damages buyer trust at launch | Manual QA review by FORGE ops before first 50 listings go live. Status requires ops approval, not just seller action. |

# **11. Infrastructure Cost — Three Tiers**

The stack is presented across three spend tiers: a near-zero bootstrapped option for pre-revenue validation, the recommended paid MVP, and a scale tier. Start at Tier 1, move to Tier 2 when you onboard your first 10 paying sellers.

## **11A. Tier 1 — Near-Zero (£0–15/month)**

For pre-revenue validation, founder testing, and recruiting founding sellers before any money changes hands. Every tool below has a free plan sufficient for the first 30–50 product listings.

| **Tool** | **Free Alternative** | **Cost** | **Free Tier Limits** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Webflow (frontend) | Framer | $0 | 1 site, custom domain, up to 1,000 pages — enough for MVP |
| Supabase (database/auth) | Supabase Free | $0 | 500MB DB, 50,000 MAUs, 1GB storage — plenty for MVP |
| Make (automation) | n8n (self-hosted) | $0 | Self-host on Railway free tier. Unlimited workflows. 500MB RAM limit. |
| Firecrawl (scraping) | Firecrawl Free | $0 | 500 scrapes/month — sufficient for first 500 seller submissions |
| Claude API | Claude API | ~$5-15 | Pay-as-you-go only. No free tier — but 50 page gens costs ~$2-3 |
| Resend (email) | Resend Free | $0 | 3,000 emails/month, 1 domain — more than enough for MVP |
| Stripe (payments) | Stripe | 2.9%+30c | No monthly fee — purely transaction-funded |
| Railway (n8n hosting) | Railway Free | $0 | $5 credit/month free — covers n8n at low usage |
| TOTAL |  | ~£5–15/mo | Only Claude API costs money at this tier |

|  | *Tier 1 trade-off: n8n requires a one-time Claude Code setup session to self-host on Railway (~45 minutes). Framer has less CMS flexibility than Webflow but is fully capable for an MVP product catalogue. The saving is ~£90/month versus the paid stack.* |
| --- | --- |

## **11B. Tier 2 — Recommended MVP (£90–120/month)**

Switch to this stack when you have 5+ paying sellers. The paid tools remove friction, increase reliability, and free you from self-hosting maintenance.

| **Tool** | **Plan** | **Monthly Cost** | **Upgrade Reason** |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Webflow | Basic ($14) or CMS ($23) | $14–23 | Custom domain + CMS collections. Upgrade to CMS when >20 products. |
| Supabase | Pro | $25 | Daily backups, 8GB DB, no cold starts, email support |
| Make | Core | $9 | Hosted, reliable, 10,000 ops/mo, no self-hosting overhead |
| Firecrawl | Hobby | $16 | 500 scrapes + faster response times + priority support |
| Claude API | Pay-as-you-go | ~$15–40 | Scales with usage. Budget $0.20 per sales page generated. |
| Resend | Free → Starter ($20) | $0–20 | Stay free until >3,000 emails/month |
| Stripe | Pay-as-you-go | 2.9%+30c | Revenue-funded — not a cost |
| TOTAL |  | ~£80–120/mo | Break-even at 4 sellers on £29/mo plan |

## **11C. Tier 3 — Scale (£250–500/month)**

Relevant at 200+ active sellers or 1,000+ product listings. By this point the platform should be generating £5,000+/month in commission and subscription revenue.

- Webflow Business ($39) or migrate to Next.js on Vercel ($20+) for full CMS flexibility

- Supabase Pro with add-ons — compute upgrades as query volume increases

- Make Teams ($29) — higher operation limits, team access

- Firecrawl Standard ($83) — 3,000 scrapes/month

- Claude API usage scales linearly — budget 15-20% of gross revenue for AI costs

|  | *Recommendation: Launch on Tier 1 (free stack). Recruit 10 founding sellers. The moment you charge your first seller subscription, move to Tier 2. Never pay for infrastructure you have not yet outgrown.* |
| --- | --- |

# **12. Immediate Next Steps**

Before opening Claude Code, complete these prerequisite actions in order:

- Create accounts: Supabase, Webflow, Make, Firecrawl, Resend, Stripe, Anthropic API. Have all API keys ready in a secure password manager before Session 1.

- Register domain (e.g. getforge.io or forge.market). Connect to Webflow immediately — DNS propagation takes up to 48 hours.

- Set up a shared environment variables document (Notion or similar) listing every API key, project URL, and credential. Claude Code will need these in every session.

- Create a Supabase project. Name it forge-mvp. Note the project URL and anon key. This is the first Claude Code session input.

- Brief 3-5 founding sellers before the platform is live. Their real product URLs will be used as test cases in Sessions 5 and 6 — real data produces better prompts than fabricated examples.

- Open Claude Code. Start Session 1 with the Supabase prompt from Section 4. Work through all 8 sessions sequentially.

|  | *Final note: This spec is written to be handed directly to Claude Code. Each labelled prompt block in this document is a verbatim (or near-verbatim) Claude Code instruction. Work session by session, validate each output before proceeding, and resist the urge to combine steps. The no-code stack was chosen specifically so that Claude Code can implement each module independently without a developer.* |
